.SH NAME
.B getemajor
\- get the external (real) major device number
.\"
.\"
.SH SYNOPSIS
.PP
.B #define _UW7_SOURCE
.br
.B #include <sys/types.h>
.br
.B #include <sys/ddi.h>
.HP
.BI "major_t getemajor(dev_t " dev );
.\"
.\"
.SH ARGUMENTS
.PP
.TP
.I dev
the device number to convert to an external (real) major.
.\"
.\"
.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
.BR getemajor (9),
.BR geteminor (9)
and
.BR makedev (9)
functions intended to supplement the
.BR getmajor (9),
.BR getminor (9)
and
.BR makedevice (9)
functions.
.PP
.BR getemajor ()
gets the external (real) device major number associated with the external
.B dev_t
device number,
.IR dev .
.BR getemajor ()
is a UWDDI specific architecture dependent macro intended to replace the
older
.I SVR 4
.[
svr4
.]
behaviour of
.BR getmajor (9).
.BR getemajor ()
is a system depdent way for a
.I STREAMS
driver or module to obtain the external (real) major device number from the
external device number.
.BR getemajor (9)
is often implemented as an architecture dependent macro, whereas
.BR getmajor ()
is an architecture independent function call.
.PP
.BR getemajor ()
is an architecture independent function that obtains the external (real) major
device number associated with device
.IR dev .
.BR getmajor (9),
on the other hand,
will return the external
.I base
major device number associated with the device
.I dev .
.PP
.BR getmajor (9)
supports the concept of extended minor device numbers.  Under extended minor
device numbering, a device has a single
.I base
major device number and an extended range of minor device numbers (exceeding
255).  Real device numbers consist of a number of major devices numbers and a
range of minor device numbers associated with each major device number from 0
to 255.
.PP
Following is an example contrasting the mapping of external major and minor
device numbers to a based major device number and an extended minor device
number:
.PP
.TS
center tab(:);
nn|nn.
_
\fBgetemajor\fR():\fBgeteminor\fR():\fBgetmajor\fR():\fBgetminor\fR()
_
32:0:32:0
":255:":255
35:0:":256
":255:":511
37:0:":512
":255:":766
_
.TE
.PP
For additional information, see section
.RI \(lq "Device Numbering" \(rq
in the
.BR "Linux Fast-STREAMS Programmer's Guide" ,
.BR SPG (9).
.\"
.\"
.SH USAGE
.PP
.BR getemajor ()
is used by drivers and modules that require knowledge of the external (real)
major device number and for use internal to the
.I STREAMS
executive.
.PP
Normally, a
.I STREAMS
module or driver
.BR qopen (9)
procedure will use the
.BR getmajor (9)
function to obtain the external
.I base
major device number and deal with the assignment of extended minor device
numbers using the
.BR getminor (9)
and
.BR makedevice (9)
functions.
.\"
.\"
.SH RETURN
.PP
.BR getemajor ()
returns the external (real) major device number associated with device
.IR dev .
.\"
.\"
.SH ERRORS
.PP
.BR getemajor ()
always succeeds.
.\"
.\"
.SH CONTEXT
.PP
.BR getemajor ()
can be called from any context, including user context, module procedures,
callouts, callbacks, soft interrupts and interrupt service routines.
.\"
.\"
.SH MP-STREAMS
.PP
.BR getemajor ()
is MP-safe.
.\"
.\"
.SH NOTICES
.PP
.BR getemajor ()
is a
.IR UnixWare \(rg-
and
.IR SUPER-UX \(rg-specific
macro:
.B _UW7_SOURCE
must be defined before including DDI/DKI include files to expose this symbol.
.B Linux Fast-STREAMS
.[
lfs
.]
must also have been compiled with
.B CONFIG_STREAMS_COMPAT_UW7
or
.B CONFIG_STREAMS_COMPAT_UW7_MODULE
defined.
.\"
.\"
.SH IMPLEMENTATION
.PP
.BR getemajor ()
uses
.BR MAJOR (9)
to obtain the external major device number.
.\"
.\"
